'''Yasakani no Magatama''' (八尺瓊勾玉) is one of the [[Imperial Regalia of Japan]] (Sanshu no Jingi) in [[Japanese mythology]], alongside the {{ill|Yata no Kagami|ja|八咫鏡|12=draft|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Kusanagi no Tsurugi|ja|天叢雲剣|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is also written as 八坂瓊曲玉.
== Form == It is said to either be a large {{ill|Magatama|ja|勾玉|12=draft|12=draft}} or magatama strung together on a long cord.
=== Interpretation of the Name === [[File:Magatama40.JPG|thumb|Magatama made of agate (example image)]] The term "saka" is usually a corruption of "shaku" (尺, a unit of measurement)<ref>『{{ill|Kojien|ja|広辞苑|12=draft|12=draft}}』and other dictionaries</ref>, but in this case, it may refer to the ancient unit of length [[Ata (unit)|咫]] (ata){{Citation needed|date=October 2012}}. Eight shaku is approximately 180 centimeters (cm) by ancient standards, while eight ata is about 140 cm.
This length may refer to the circumference of the jewel, its total length including its "tail," or the length of the cord attached to it. Additionally, "eight shaku" could simply imply great size or length. Another theory suggests that "yasaka" derives from "iyasaka" (弥栄), meaning "prosperity."
The word "ni" (瓊) refers to beautiful jewels, particularly red gems. It is thus considered to be made of {{ill|Agate|ja|メノウ|12=draft|12=draft}}, as red agate was commonly used for magatama and other ornaments in modern {{ill|Wakasa agate crafts|ja|若狭めのう細工|12=draft|12=draft}}. This red color often results from a heating process developed in the Edo period.
In the {{ill|Fudoki|ja|風土記|12=draft|12=draft}}, specifically an excerpt from the {{ill|Echigo Fudoki|ja|越後国風土記|12=draft|12=draft}}, it is described as "Yasakani is the name of the jewel. It is said that the jewel's color is blue, hence the name 'Ao-Yasakani no Tama' (青八坂丹の玉)." This suggests it was likely a jade magatama or at least perceived as such. Jade magatama were highly valued, as evidenced by artifacts from the {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft|12=draft}} and references in Chinese historical texts.
== Symbolism == Also called a "jewel" (璽)<ref>璽 originally referred to "the seal of a noble person" ({{ill|Wiktionary|en|璽|12=draft|12=draft}}). In Japan, the emperor's seals are referred to as御璽 or国璽 ([https://kotobank.jp/word/璽-515296 Kotobank - 璽]).</ref>, it is associated with the other two treasures and referred to collectively as {{ill|Kenji|ja|剣璽|12=draft|12=draft}}.
The {{ill|Yoro Code|ja|養老令|12=draft|12=draft}}'s section on {{ill|Jingi|ja|神祇令|12=draft|12=draft}} states: {{Quotation|On the day of [[Accession to the Chrysanthemum Throne|践祚]], the {{ill|Imibe clan|ja|忌部氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, shall present the sacred mirror and sword (神璽の鏡剣).}} The {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}} records that during the accession of {{ill|Empress Jitō|ja|持統天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} in [[690]], the Imibe clan presented the "sacred mirror and sword." Although there is no explicit mention of the jewel, several theories attempt to address this omission<ref name="kotobank">{{cite | url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E4%B8%89%E7%A8%AE%E3%81%AE%E7%A5%9E%E5%99%A8%28%E5%AE%9D%E7%89%A9%29-1540193#E6.97.A5.E6.9C.AC.E5.A4.A7.E7.99.BE.E7.A7.91.E5.85.A8.E6.9B.B8.28.E3.83.8B.E3.83.83.E3.83.9D.E3.83.8B.E3.82.AB.29 | title=[[Japan Encyclopedia]] | chapter=三種の神器（宝物） | publisher=[[Shogakukan]] | author=Kojirō Naoki }}</ref>: * The jewel was always part of the treasures but was considered personal adornment rather than an object to be presented. * The term "sacred mirror and sword" might be a shorthand for the complete set of three treasures.
== Location == === Historical Background === In the {{ill|Nara period|ja|奈良時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, it was kept in the court's treasury. During the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, it, along with the sword, was stored in a chest near the emperor<ref name="kotobank"/>.
There are accounts, such as during the reign of {{ill|Emperor Reizei|ja|冷泉天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}, of attempts to open the container housing the jewel, resulting in mysterious occurrences that deterred further examination<ref name="kyokasyo22">{{Cite web|author=Takehito Takeda|url=https://www.fujitv.co.jp/takeshi/takeshi/column/koshitsu/koshitsu22.html|title=皇室のきょうかしょ Vol.22 八尺瓊曲玉|publisher=Fujitv|accessdate=2019-05-06}}</ref>.
In the {{ill|Genpei War|ja|源平合戦|12=draft|12=draft}}, during the {{ill|Battle of Dan-no-ura|ja|壇ノ浦の戦い|12=draft|12=draft}} (1185), it sank into the sea along with {{ill|Emperor Antoku|ja|安徳天皇|1=Emperor Antoku|2=ja|3=安徳天皇|4=de|5=Antoku|12=draft|12=draft}}, but it was recovered, reportedly floating in its case.
=== Current Status === The Yasakani no Magatama is now housed in the {{ill|Imperial Palace|ja|皇居|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was last ceremonially moved during the {{ill|2019 Japanese Imperial transition|ja|平成から令和への皇位継承|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref>{{Cite news |date=2019-05-01 |title=New Emperor's Commitment |url=https://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXMZO44379480R00C19A5MM0000/|publisher=[[Nihon Keizai Shimbun]] |accessdate=2024-04-21 }}</ref>.
== References ==
{{reflist|2}} == See Also == * {{ill|Three Sacred Treasures of Japan|ja|三種の神器|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Regalia|ja|レガリア|12=draft|12=draft}}
== External Links == *{{Kotobank|三種の神器（宝物）}} *{{Kotobank|三種の神器}}
